          "body": "Three times Jesus names *the end of the age* (13:39, 40, 49). At that point the Son of Man sends His angels to gather out of His kingdom all stumbling blocks and lawless ones (13:41), and the dragnet's catch is sorted — good fish kept, bad thrown away (13:48-50). The imagery is unrelenting: *furnace of fire*, *weeping and gnashing of teeth* (13:42, 50). Modern sensibilities recoil; Jesus refuses to soften it. The same Lord who teaches the joy of finding treasure (13:44) teaches the horror of being separated from the kingdom. Both are necessary, and both are taught by the same authoritative voice. The chapter forbids any kingdom-theology that omits the final judgment."
